---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import SectionHeader from '../../components/SectionHeader.astro';
import PullQuote from '../../components/PullQuote.astro';
import Annotation from '../../components/Annotation.astro';
import Sample from '../../components/Sample.astro';
---
<Base title="Behavioral Empathy" section={6}>
  <article class="prose">

    <SectionHeader
      n={6}
      title="Behavioral Empathy"
      meta="~600 words · 2 interactive samples"
    />

    <p>
      There is a class of design decisions that don't appear in any style guide
      because they aren't visual. They're behavioral. They live in how the
      interface responds to the user's actions — not just to explicit gestures
      like clicking a button, but to implicit ones like scrolling up mid-stream,
      or typing a second sentence into the input box. These decisions are the
      subtlest and, cumulatively, the most keenly felt.
    </p>

    <p>
      Behavioral empathy is the practice of designing those responses with the
      same intentionality you bring to color and type. It means asking, for
      every piece of dynamic behavior: what is the user trying to signal here,
      and is the interface interpreting that signal correctly?
    </p>

    <PullQuote>
      These aren't features. They're the interface paying attention.
    </PullQuote>

    <h2>Auto-scroll that knows when to stop</h2>

    <p>
      During text generation, auto-scrolling keeps the latest output visible
      without the user needing to chase it manually. This is the right default.
      But the moment a user scrolls up — to re-read something, to check an
      earlier claim, to copy a specific line — the auto-scroll must stop
      immediately and completely.
    </p>

    <p>
      Failing to do this is one of the most common and most frustrating
      behavioral errors in streaming UIs. The user scrolls up with intent.
      The interface drags them back down. The implicit message: <em>your
      actions don't matter here.</em> This is not a minor UX complaint.
      It's a trust failure.
    </p>

    <Sample label="Interactive sample — auto-scroll with intent detection">
      <div style="font-family: system-ui, sans-serif; font-size: 13px; color: #4a3728;">

        <div style="display: flex; gap: 8px; margin-bottom: 12px; align-items: center;">
          <button id="s6-scroll-btn" onclick="s6StartScroll()" style="font-family: system-ui, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; letter-spacing: 0.06em; text-transform: uppercase; background: #fdf3e8; border: 0.5px solid #e8c9a0; color: #8b6345; border-radius: 6px; padding: 5px 12px; cursor: pointer;">▶ Start stream</button>
          <span id="s6-scroll-status" style="font-size: 12px; color: #a08060;">Auto-scroll: on</span>
        </div>

        <div
          id="s6-scroll-box"
          style="height: 140px; overflow-y: auto; background: #f7f0e6; border-radius: 8px; border: 0.5px solid #e4d9cc; padding: 12px 16px; font-family: 'Lora', Georgia, serif; font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.8; color: #4a3728; scroll-behavior: smooth;"
        >
          <div id="s6-scroll-content" style="display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 6px;"></div>
        </div>

        <div style="margin-top: 8px; font-size: 11px; color: #a08060; letter-spacing: 0.04em; text-transform: uppercase;">
          Scroll up during generation to pause auto-scroll. Scroll back to bottom to resume.
        </div>
      </div>
      <script>
        (function() {
          const lines = [
            "The interface that pays attention is the one you trust.",
            "Trust is built through a thousand small demonstrations of intent.",
            "Auto-scroll keeps the latest thought visible without friction.",
            "But the moment you scroll up — to re-read, to check, to copy —",
            "the interface should recognize that intent immediately.",
            "And stop. Completely. Without fighting you.",
            "This is what behavioral empathy looks like in practice.",
            "Not a grand gesture. A quiet act of respect.",
          ];
          let scrollInterval = null;
          let autoScroll = true;
          let lineIndex = 0;

          function s6StartScroll() {
            const box = document.getElementById('s6-scroll-box');
            const content = document.getElementById('s6-scroll-content');
            const btn = document.getElementById('s6-scroll-btn');
            const status = document.getElementById('s6-scroll-status');
            if (!box || !content || !btn) return;

            // Reset
            content.innerHTML = '';
            lineIndex = 0;
            autoScroll = true;
            btn.disabled = true;
            btn.textContent = '…';
            if (status) status.textContent = 'Auto-scroll: on';

            // Detect user scroll intent
            let userScrolled = false;
            const handleScroll = () => {
              const atBottom = box.scrollTop + box.clientHeight >= box.scrollHeight - 8;
              if (!atBottom) {
                autoScroll = false;
                userScrolled = true;
                if (status) status.textContent = 'Auto-scroll: paused (scrolled up)';
              } else if (userScrolled) {
                autoScroll = true;
                if (status) status.textContent = 'Auto-scroll: resumed';
              }
            };
            box.addEventListener('scroll', handleScroll, { passive: true });

            if (scrollInterval) clearInterval(scrollInterval);
            scrollInterval = setInterval(() => {
              if (lineIndex >= lines.length) {
                clearInterval(scrollInterval);
                box.removeEventListener('scroll', handleScroll);
                if (btn) { btn.disabled = false; btn.textContent = '▶ Start stream'; }
                if (status) status.textContent = 'Stream complete';
                return;
              }
              const p = document.createElement('p');
              p.textContent = lines[lineIndex];
              p.style.margin = '0';
              p.style.opacity = '0';
              p.style.transform = 'translateY(6px)';
              p.style.transition = 'opacity 360ms cubic-bezier(.4,0,.2,1), transform 360ms cubic-bezier(.4,0,.2,1)';
              content.appendChild(p);
              requestAnimationFrame(() => requestAnimationFrame(() => {
                p.style.opacity = '1';
                p.style.transform = 'translateY(0)';
              }));
              lineIndex++;
              if (autoScroll) box.scrollTo({ top: box.scrollHeight, behavior: 'smooth' });
            }, 700);
          }
          window.s6StartScroll = s6StartScroll;
        })();
      </script>
    </Sample>

    <h2>The input that adapts to you</h2>

    <p>
      The input box growing as you type is the other canonical example.
      A fixed-height input with a scrollbar inside it forces the user to
      compose through a slot. They can't see their own writing. The mental
      model of the message gets compressed into a horizontal slot that
      has nothing to do with how thoughts are structured.
    </p>

    <p>
      An auto-growing input collapses the difference between composing
      a question and composing a paragraph. You write. The space expands.
      The interface adapts to the content rather than the content adapting
      to the interface.
    </p>

    <Sample label="Interactive sample — adaptive input height">
      <div style="font-family: system-ui, sans-serif; font-size: 13px; color: #4a3728;">
        <div style="display: flex; gap: 12px; margin-bottom: 16px; align-items: start;">

          <!-- Fixed input -->
          <div style="flex: 1;">
            <div style="font-size: 11px; color: #a08060; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.06em; margin-bottom: 6px;">Fixed height</div>
            <div style="background: #f7f0e6; border: 0.5px solid #e4d9cc; border-radius: 8px; padding: 10px 12px; height: 44px; overflow: hidden;">
              <textarea
                placeholder="Type here…"
                style="width: 100%; height: 100%; background: none; border: none; outline: none; resize: none; font-family: 'Lora', Georgia, serif; font-size: 15px; color: #4a3728; line-height: 1.6;"
              ></textarea>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Growing input -->
          <div style="flex: 1;">
            <div style="font-size: 11px; color: #8b6345; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.06em; margin-bottom: 6px; font-weight: 500;">Adaptive height ✓</div>
            <div id="s6-grow-wrap" style="background: #fdf3e8; border: 0.5px solid #e8c9a0; border-radius: 8px; padding: 10px 12px;">
              <textarea
                id="s6-grow-input"
                placeholder="Type here…"
                rows="1"
                oninput="s6Grow(this)"
                style="width: 100%; background: none; border: none; outline: none; resize: none; font-family: 'Lora', Georgia, serif; font-size: 15px; color: #4a3728; line-height: 1.6; display: block; overflow: hidden; transition: height 120ms cubic-bezier(.4,0,.2,1);"
              ></textarea>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div style="font-size: 11px; color: #c8ad94; letter-spacing: 0.04em; text-transform: uppercase;">
          The interface adapts to you — not the other way around
        </div>
      </div>
      <script>
        (function() {
          function s6Grow(el) {
            el.style.height = 'auto';
            el.style.height = el.scrollHeight + 'px';
          }
          window.s6Grow = s6Grow;
        })();
      </script>
    </Sample>

    <Annotation label="On loading skeletons">
      Loading states are behavioral design too. The warm loading skeleton
      — a pulsing <code>--paper-1</code> placeholder rather than a cold
      grey shimmer — carries the design language into the most uncertain
      moment of the interaction. The user is waiting. What they see while
      waiting is the interface's most honest self-portrait.
    </Annotation>

    <p>
      None of these behaviors is technically difficult. Detecting a scroll
      event, resizing a textarea, choosing a warm shimmer over a grey one —
      each takes an afternoon. What takes longer is the decision to care about
      them at all. Behavioral empathy isn't a feature you add at the end. It's
      a disposition you maintain throughout, asking at every turn: what is this
      person actually trying to do right now, and is the interface helping or
      getting in the way?
    </p>

  </article>
</Base>
